rged an alternative way of thinking about the organization of modern politics. They did this in part by going back to the foundations: rejecting Hobbes's vision of human nature and his arguements about our capacity to form stable societies over time. In turn, this was harnessed to a deep reconceptualization of how to think philosophically about politics in a secular world. The result was an emphasis on the "opinion of mankind," the necessary psychological basis of all political organization. Demonstrating how Hume and Smith broke away from Hobbesian state theory, The Opinion of Mankind also suggests ways in which these thinkers might shape how we think about politics today, and in turn how we might construct better political theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aPolitical sciencexHistory. 0aState, The. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAdam Smith.  aAnthony Ashley Cooper.  aBernard Mandeville.  aDavid Hume.  aFrancis Hutcheson.  aImmanuel Kant.  aJean-Jacques Rousseau.  aJohn Locke.  aScottish Enlightenment.  aThe Social Contract.  aThomas Hobbes.  aWestern political thought.  aauthority.  acommercial sociability.  ademocracy.  afamily.  agovernment.  ahistory.  ahuman nature.  ahuman psychology.  ajustice.  amodern state.  aopinion of mankind.  aopinion.  aphilosophy.  apity.  apolitical obligation.  apolitical theory.  apolitical thought.  apride.  aproperty.  asecular world.  asociability.  asovereignty.  astate of nature.  asympathy.  atheory of politics.  atheory of regime forms.  atheory of the state.  autility.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook packag